snippet.textDisplay: When our everyday familiar reality is faced against a force that forms an hostile opposition to that, a state of disarray is destined to manifest out of spiritual urgency. And so we begin our fierce and rigid pursuit of the monsters we fear, often generating a bit more then a healthy dose of self righteousness and adamancy to tread to the places where we believe the things are that the living daylight should not bare. Often in blatant disregard for common civility and sometimes even worse. When the conclusion of the hunt turns out to be hollow or in any other way unsatisfactory, we are obliged to put the means that led us to where we are now under a lens of honest scrutiny. It is there that the realization seeps in that we ourselves in some shape or form have become the very monsters we fear so much. At this point feelings of guilt and disillusionment strike us down. At the collapse of the world as we used to know it and lest we forget the insatiable nature of our morbid curiosities, we then start to look for answers from within, as we entangle ourselves up with the worst versions of ourselves, in plight to make some kind of sense of it all. Within a web of grotesqueness as such, salvation can solely be reached through puritanical visionhood.

snippet.textDisplay:
I think that red glow that follows her is rage, as she presents it with her first word in the song.
So, rage is following her, and she's naked trying to escape. Naked because she's vulnerable.
I've no idea why the house or the entering by the window, but she covers herself in petals for armor not being naked anymore... i mean, as a way to stop being vulnerable.
Then she faces rage, defeating it.
But she now realizes rage is herself. It's her own rage, it's part of herself. So she thought she had tamed, but it's just lying in wait.

snippet.textDisplay:
I find it fucking hilarious how I was trashed by a lot of people years ago for saying that Paramore was going down the same road No Doubt did, back in the early to mid 2000s.

Well look at Paramore now, they completely changed their sound from what they used to be and Haley has put out a solo album completely devoid of resembling music she once played.

Now there's people that say "Oh Haley said they're going to go back into the studio once her solo albums out." while this might be true and they do go back into the studio, I would not expect them to last that much longer past that album.
